<DOC><DOCNO> AP880712-0146 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1445EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Melton-Profile     07-12 0201</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Melton-Profile,200</SECOND><HEAD>Ambassador on Duty in Managua Only 2 Months Before Ouster</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Career diplomat Richard Melton served only twomonths as ambassador to Nicaragua before the Sandinista governmentordered him out of the country on grounds of interfering inNicaragua's internal affairs.   Melton, 52, is one of the State Department's most experiencedCentral America experts and is considered close to AssistantSecretary of State Elliott Abrams. He is known around the StateDepartment for his low-key style.   Before his appointment to Managua, Melton served as director ofthe State Department's office of Central American affairs.   In early 1987, he took an interim assignment as head of the U.S.Embassy in Costa Rica after Ambassador Lewis Tambs resigned andreturned to private life.   Melton arrived in Managua on April 12, a period of high hopesbecause of a temporary cease-fire signed three weeks earlier by theSandinistas and the Contra rebels. He presented his credentials toPresident Daniel Ortega in May.   Melton is a 27-year veteran of the foreign service. His firstforeign assignment was as political officer in Managua in 1963during the rule of the Somoza family dynasty. He speaks Spanish andPortuguese.</TEXT></DOC>